Hi,

I also had issues with schema marshalling so I decided to take a step back and try to get it to work with the supplied basic TodoMVC example.

On the `10.0.1` dist I was able to successfully get marshalling with `schema_model` to work. E.g.

```
todo = api.schema_model('Todo', {
    'properties': {
        'id': {
            'type': 'string'
        },
        'task': {
            'type': 'string'
        }
    },
    'type': 'object'
})
```

```
@ns.route('/')
class TodoList(Resource):
    '''Shows a list of all todos, and lets you POST to add new tasks'''
    @ns.doc('list_todos')
    @ns.marshal_list_with(todo)
    def get(self):
        '''List all tasks'''
        return DAO.todos

    @ns.doc('create_todo')
    @ns.expect(todo)
    @ns.marshal_with(todo, code=201)
    def post(self):
        '''Create a new task'''
        return DAO.create(api.payload), 201
```

I believe your issue stands with the fact that your schema object is malformed. The root object should be 'properties', and you'll want to with a list of fields and their types, just like it is explained in the JSON Schema structure established by the *Draft v4* standard: http://json-schema.org/examples.html

Hoping this helps!

Until the Django bug is fixed you should make sure to run a data migration that update the content type associated with your model from `OldName` to `NewName`.

e.g.

```
#!python
def rename_my_model_content_type(apps, schema_editor)
    content_types = apps.get_model('contenttypes.ContentType').objects
    assert content_types.filter(
        app_label='my_app', model='MyOldModelName'.lower()
    ).update(model='MyNewModelName'.lower()) == 1
```

