@hmaarrfk I do not understand why you need a tag to keep track of the information you need.  We have `HEAD` which is the latest development version (and the version is defined in `skimage.__version__`).  We then have a maintenance branch, like `v0.14.x`, tracking point releases.  You can use `git` itself to find the ancestor of `v0.14.x` and `master` if you need to isolate the branch point commit.

>I think we should go this way (convert2ycbcr=True) because setting the precedent that skimage functions could expect images in any colorspace is quite a big can of worms. 

@jni I actually think that it is better to have these things explicit. Keeping our images in pure numpy-arrays doesn't mean that we have to avoid the idea of metadata handling. With the current state of affairs, either we should have all functions taking `img, metadata` (where `metadata` is some kind of dict or list of previous operations applied on `img`) as a first pair of arguments, or we have to expose those keys of `metadata` as a separate parameters.
This could lead us close to the "hell" similar to the signature of http://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/generated/pandas.read_csv.html, but is actually a way to write clear, explicit, highly-configurable image processing functions without opening a "can of warnings and unhandled cases." :wink: 

@stsievert I've given this one more round, and I'd agree with your proposal to have `convert2ycbcr` parameter with `False` by default. Well, unless the roundtrip conversion is non-destructive (i.e. `img == ycbcr2rgb(rgb2ycbcr(img))`), which is not the case, I suppose.
And, I guess, we drop `_rgb2colorspace(img, space)` and the inverse function for now.

I couldn't find any explicitly defined `__hash__` method defined in ExtensionClass.Base, so my guess is that some built-in fallback hashing mechanism is used which is different between Python2 and Python3.

Experimenting at the command line showed that simply hashing `__data__` won't be enough. Currently under Python 2, even Record objects with the same `__data__` and identical `__record_schema__` hash differently.

A `__hash__` method that will show similar behavior and hash any record object uniquely:

    def __hash__(self):
        return hash(str(self))

What do you think?

