Yes. Linux memory implementation would solve _all_ (normally not just a sample) possible targets of the symbolic index on a memory access and build the resultant expression. That's eagerly.
The lazy option is to express the same thing in terms of an smtlib array. 

For both cases the problem is when the symbolic index has too many solutions.
Doing it eagerly makes it easy for the solver down the way but won't handle the case in which the index has a lot of solutions but only a few matter.

I most cases the lazy approach wont get too far neither if the index has a lot of solutions but it allows for the case in which you do not need to solve it (or in which the index gets constrained after the access?)

This is something the eagerly approach with fail at: 
```
index = input();
memory[10] = 100;
memory[200] = 200;
if (memory[index] < 150)
   printf( "Oh!");
else
  printf("Ah!");
```

