@divyanks I can confirm that naming an image afterwards (based on the id that shows up in `docker ps`) works. However, the problem is that it's hard to fully automate this step as part of our release process if the naming/tagging doesn't work that way.

The good news is: Based on this [SO answer](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/38457669/docker-build-with-dockerfile-but-the-image-has-no-name-or-tag
) I figured out what's wrong. We have to drop the final `RUN trinity` or otherwise the last step (which is naming the image) won't get executed. I think we can instead simply print out something that tells the user to either type `trinity` or `trinity --help` from there.

I also noticed that if you run `docker run -it <image-name>` it will start into a Python REPL which is probably not what we want.

